    {
        "content": "<p>I am new to lean. I am attempting to prove the following:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">prob_union_le_sum_probs</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ω</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ProbabilityMeasure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ω</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∪</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span>\n<span class=\"n\">begin</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- Your proof goes here</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">end</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>How can I import ProbabilityMeasure? I tried </p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">MeasureTheory</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>but it does not resolve the entire module, it searches (and fails to find) Mathlib/MeasureTheory.lean.</p>\n<p>Any idea how I can get this import, besides searching for and importing the exact file that contains ProbabilityMeasure?</p>",
        "id": 490974329,
        "sender_full_name": "Washington Irving",
        "timestamp": 1735294131
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By importing the exact file that contains ProbabilityMeasure</p>",
        "id": 490974841,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1735294474
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or <code>import Mathlib</code> for the entire library</p>",
        "id": 490974852,
        "sender_full_name": "Ruben Van de Velde",
        "timestamp": 1735294482
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can use <code>import Mathlib</code> to import everything. I recall some talk about files you can import for specific subjects, but I don't think that's implemented yet, so if you want something finer than <code>import Mathlib</code> you'll have to figure out the exact files to import.<br>\nNote that after using <code>import Mathlib</code> you can use <code>#min_imports</code> to find the relevant files</p>",
        "id": 490974863,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1735294487
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(By the way, <code>ProbabilityMeasure</code> is actually <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.ProbabilityMeasure#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.ProbabilityMeasure</a>, so you need to either <code>open MeasureTheory</code>/<code>namespace MeasureTheory</code> or use the full name. Additionally <code>begin</code> and <code>end</code> are Lean 3 syntax, you should do</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">prob_union_le_sum_probs</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Set</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ω</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ProbabilityMeasure</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Ω</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∪</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≤</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">prob</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>)</p>",
        "id": 490975025,
        "sender_full_name": "Daniel Weber",
        "timestamp": 1735294573
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Also you should probably not use <code>ProbabilityMeasure</code>, but instead a <code>Measure</code>with property <code>IsProbabilityMeasure</code>. See <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/blog/posts/basic-probability-in-mathlib/\">https://leanprover-community.github.io/blog/posts/basic-probability-in-mathlib/</a> for an explanation (and more remarks about how to do probability in Mathlib).</p>",
        "id": 490975196,
        "sender_full_name": "Rémy Degenne",
        "timestamp": 1735294697
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks all for the suggestions. I was able to resolve my issue simply with:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span>\n</code></pre></div>",
